<p>Do you sometimes feel like this?</p>
<p>If so then read on and learn how to manage all those monkeys
  (a word used to describe &quot;next moves&quot; that you need to manage)
  that are running wild and driving you CRAZY!</p>
<p>In a wonderful little book called the &quot;One Minute Manager&quot;
  the concept of monkey management was born. <br>
  <br>
  <img class="img-fluid"  alt="One Minute Manager"

                     src="{{ asset('storage/images/one%20minute%20manager.png') }}"
                       > <br>
  <br>
  Essentially a monkey is the <strong>&quot;next step&quot;</strong> in a
  series of steps towards a goal! <br>
  The &quot;next step&quot; is either your responsibility or belongs to
  someone else. <br>
  But if the &quot;next step&quot; is not done then the achievement of the
  goal is delayed or frustrated. <br>
  <br>
  Imagine you are a manager and your staff member stops you in
  the passage, while you are on your way to a meeting. &quot;I have to
  talk to you!?&quot; &quot;Its urgent!&quot; <br>
  <br>
  And before you know it your member of staff has you pinned up
  against the side of the corridor and when they are finished with
  you they walk off happily (with a bounce in their step) and you
  look around and you see the staff member's monkey (problem /
  next step in an action) sitting happily on your shoulder.&nbsp; </p>
<p> <img class="img-fluid"  alt="" src="{{ asset('storage/images/monkeyonyourback.png') }}" ></p>
<p>They have just made their problem your problem! <br>
  <br>
  In life we all have tasks to do. <br>
  These tasks (jobs) are normally defined in our job description
  or in our role. <br>
  <br>
  These jobs or tasks are our monkeys. <br>
  It is for us to manage these monkeys. I.e. We need to manage
  them and control them (as if they were out very own pets I.e.
  look after them, clean them and feed them) etc. <br>
  <br>
  But many people often do not like their own monkeys because
  they can be difficult to take care of and are hard work. <br>
  <br>
  So they develop excellent skills in passing their monkeys off
  onto other people. <br>
  Especially Bosses and Project Managers! <br>
  <br>
  An effective Boss or Project Manager ensures that monkeys stay
  on the shoulders of the staff members they have employed to care
  for these monkeys.&nbsp; An effective manager does not allow a
  staff member to offload monkeys on other staff members or onto
  him or herself. If a staff member has difficulties with a monkey
  then a manager must help the staff member but NEVER take over
  ownership of the monkey or allow it to jump onto his or her own
  shoulders. <br>
  <br>
  Roles in a marriage can also be seen as monkeys. I.e. a wife
  who hates to cook is always insisting that her husband take them
  out to eat and therefore wastes family money. Or a husband who
  will not manage his monkey of taking out the trash etc. When the
  wife comes into the kitchen and looks at the bin, there sits his
  monkey, chattering at her on the trash bin still overflowing
  with trash! <br>
  <br>
  Children can also become expert at creating conditions where
  their parents feel the need to take over their monkeys.&nbsp;
  Part of the training for life of a child is ensuring that they
  learn to be responsible and to manage their own monkeys and not
  to offload responsibilities which should be theirs, onto others. <br>
  <br>
  If you can manage &quot;your own monkeys&quot; well then you will always
  be assured of a job. <br>
  Managers love staff who are able to manage their own monkeys!</p>
<p> And here is a trick! <br>
  <br>
  To effectively manage<strong> 'your own monkeys'</strong> always deal with the
  most nasty, unpredictable and potentially dangerous ones first!</p>
<p> <img class="img-fluid"  alt="Sort me NOW!"

                     src="{{ asset('storage/images/rabidmonkey2.png') }}"
                     ></p>
<p>In the morning when you look at the many things you have on
  your &quot;To Do List&quot;. Put the two most dangerous monkeys on the
  desk in front of you and deal with them first, NOW IMMEDIATELY!&nbsp;
  Its absolutely OK to procrastinate with the other monkey's on
  your list&nbsp; I.e. the less nasty and dangerous ones. You can
  get to them later when you have handled the two most dangerous
  ones first! <br>
  <br>
  After you have summoned up the courage and handled the first
  two then choose the next in the list from most dangerous to
  least dangerous. <br>
  <br>
  You will be amazed how wonderful you will feel when you have a
  handle on your monkeys. <br>
  Try it now! You will not be sorry!</p>
